Date: 0/0/1898
Source: NZ Contemp. Dict. Suppl. (Collins)
Author: MORRIS
Vol / Page: 444
Edition:
Quote: <i>Summer Country, n.</i> In New Zealand (South Island), country which can be used in summer only; mountain land in Otago and Canterbury, above a certain level.
Notes:

Date: 0/0/1922
Source: NZ Sheepfarming
Author: PERRY
Vol / Page: 88
Edition:
Quote: The higher country, and that having a southerly aspect, which is likely to hold snow to some depth in the winter months, is termed `summer country', for it is unsafe for sheep in the winter, and is used only for summer grazing.
Notes:

Date: 0/0/1949
Source: High Country Days
Author: NEWTON
Vol / Page: 197
Edition:
Quote: In high country a lot of the country, i.e., the hinterland and higher areas, carries too much snow to carry any sheep in the winter. Accordingly, it is only stocked in the summer and is known as `summer country.' Conversely, safe country which is saved for the winter is `winter country.'
Notes: (1950),  (Gloss.)

